<P>
TAUNTING AT BORDER PROBED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Border Patrol in San Diego will begin an inquiry into an incident late 
Sunday in which an agent taunted hundreds of undocumented immigrants for more 
than an hour with slurs amplified over his vehicle's public address system. 
Michael D. Gregg, supervisory patrol agent, said the patrol would "look into" 
the taunting, which was witnessed by journalists and occurred Sunday evening 
along the Tijuana River in San Diego, a major crossing point for those seeking 
to enter the United States from Mexico without documentation. The incident 
comes at a time when Border Patrol officials have maintained that they face 
increasing threats of violence from hostile crowds of would-be immigrants who 
mass along the border each evening, occasionally harassing the agents verbally 
and pelting them with rocks. Less than two hours after the taunting was 
overheard, a Border Patrol agent near the same area shot and wounded a 
15-year-old Mexican boy who patrol agents say was about to hurl a rock at 
another agent. 
</P>
