<TEXT>
<P>
T-Bill Rates Mixed: The Treasury sold $7.2 billion of new three-month bills at 
an average discount rate of 7.94%, down from 7.99% last week. Another $7.2 
billion of new six-month bills was sold at an average discount rate of 7.88%, 
up from 7.85% last week. The new discount rates understate the actual return to 
investors -- 8.21% for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for 
$9,799.30 and 8.32% for a six-month bill selling for $9,601.60. The discount 
rate reflects the price discount received when they are purchased at less than 
face value. In a separate report, the Federal Reserve reported that the average 
yield for one-year T-bills, the most popular index for making changes in 
adjustable-rate mortgages, rose to 8.36% last week, up from 8.30% the previous 
week. 
</P>
