<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
UNREST CUTS CHINESE TOURISM IN HALF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIJING 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign tourism to China plummeted in July to nearly half the level of July, 
1988, but made a modest recovery from June following the bloody crackdown on 
the democracy movement, a report in the official English-language China Daily 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
The country earned $2.2 billion last year from tourism, but analysts expect the 
industry will finish this year earning only half that figure. The peak summer 
season has been largely written off. 
</P>
<P>
Major hotels are operating at or below 50% occupancy, with some as low as 20%. 
The National Tourism Administration said only 80,000 foreign nationals entered 
the country in July, a 47.5% drop from July, 1988, but a modest 11.3% increase 
over June, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
